flowRoot.flowPara: This was our first rocket and a proof of concept for some of our radio systems, including real-time broadcast video. It was a great introduction to amateur rocketry for many of us.

LV1 was our next rocket that flew to 3.6km (12,000ft). It was our proof of concept for several new systems, including a emergency uplink system, inertial sensors, and a more advanced telemetry system.

Flew LV1, same as the last launch. We made a major upgrade to the avionics system: added GPS, upgraded the flight computer and improved the inertial measurement unit. This was our step towards the ability to do active guidance.
LV2 is the next generation in airframes. This was a airframe test flight flown without custom avionics. Instead a commercial flight computer was installed to open the chutes and measure altitude.
This was a hasty test of another LV2 airframe. We tried to launch despite some trouble with the fin can which ended up coming off a few seconds into the flight.

Using the surviving airframe from the LV2.1 we added the patch antennas and a full flight computer stack. Unfortunately the black powder charges didn't burn and the recovery system failed. However the electronics were a great success.

We were disheartened by loss of two vehicles in a row. We took some time off to rebuild and redesign with more testing and redundancy. We tested all components fully before launch. The flight was successful except for misaligned fins causing excessive spin (this was ultimately harmless).
We imple-mented a set of canards that would turn to counteract roll. While the launch and recovery was flawless the roll control failed to maintain control.
Fixed the roll issue with a spinning "fin can". Near perfect flight.
Motor over-pressurized, failing the casing just after ignition. Technically flew, but only a few feet. The vehicle itself was unharmed.
We finished our custom Linux flight computer build and tested the computer, antennas and new 360 camera module.
Further testing and refinement of our flight computer, this time having direct control (but no closed loop control) of the roll fins.
Our last flight on LV2 hardware, this was the culmination of the LV2 program. We had student build flight computer hardware and ground software controlling the roll fins and cameras.

L-13 was the first test flight of LV3. It carried an electromechanical nose separation ring and spherical-view camera module. During supersonic flight, the airframe buckled and folded in half, scattering the modules across the desert. The initial April 22nd launch was scrubbed due to a hardware failure on the launch rail.
With a redesigned coupling ring system and fully electromechanical recovery system, LV3.1 will become the new PSAS test platform.
OreSat0 is our first CubeSat and Oregon's first satellite. It tested critical technologies for OreSat1.
LV4 is PSAS' entry into the Base 11 competition to launch to 100 km. It will fly on a 3D printed, electrically fed engine running on liquid oxygen and alcohol.
